gy of Henry Mayhew, Leah Price also uncovers the lives and afterlives of anonymous religious tracts and household manuals. From knickknacks to wastepaper, books mattered to the Victorians in ways that cannot be explained by their printed content alone. And whether displayed, defaced, exchanged, or discarded, printed matter participated, and still participates, in a range of transactions that stretches far beyond reading. Supplementing close readings with a sensitive reconstruction of how Victorians thought and felt about books, Price offers a new model for integrating literary theory with cultural history. How to Do Things with Books in Victorian Britain reshapes our understanding of the interplay between words and objects in the nineteenth century and beyond.  aMode of access: Internet via World Wide Web.  aIn English.0 aDescription based on online resource; title from PDF title page (publisher's Web site, viewed 29. Jul 2021) 0aBook industries and tradexHistoryx19th centuryxGreat Britain. 0aBook industries and tradezGreat BritainxHistoryy19th century. 0aBooks and reading in literature. 0aBooks and readingxHistoryx19th centuryxGreat Britain. 0aBooks and readingzGreat BritainxHistoryy19th century. 0aBooks in literaturexElectronic books. 0aBooks in literature. 0aBooksxPsychological aspectsxHistoryx19th centuryxGreat Britain. 0aBooksxSocial aspectsxHistoryx19th centuryxGreat Britain. 0aBooksxSocial aspectszGreat BritainxHistoryy19th century. 0aBookszGreat BritainxPsychological aspectsxHistoryy19th century. 0aEnglish fictionxHistory and criticismx19th century. 0aEnglish fictiony19th centuryxHistory and criticism. 7aLITERARY CRITICISM / European / English, Irish, Scottish, Welsh.2bisacsh  aAnthony Trollope.  aDavid Copperfield.  aEnlightenment.  aEvangelical publishers.  aGeorge Gissing.  aHenry Mayhew.  aVictorians.  aantisocial genre.  aauthors.  abildungsroman.  abook buying.  